### Document Structure
- `<!DOCTYPE>`: Defines the document type.
- `<html>`: Root element of an HTML document.
- `<head>`: Contains meta-information about the document.
- `<body>`: Contains the content of the document.

### Metadata
- `<title>`: Sets the title of the document (shown in the browser's title bar or tab).
- `<meta>`: Provides metadata such as character set, page description, keywords, author of the document, and viewport settings.
- `<link>`: Defines the relationship between the current document and an external resource (used for linking to stylesheets).
- `<style>`: Contains CSS styling rules.
- `<base>`: Specifies the base URL for all relative URLs in a document.

### Content Sectioning
- `<header>`: Represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids.
- `<nav>`: Defines a set of navigation links.
- `<section>`: Defines a section in a document.
- `<article>`: Represents a self-contained piece of content that can be independently distributed or reused.
- `<aside>`: Represents a portion of a document whose content is only indirectly related to the document's main content.
- `<footer>`: Represents the footer for its nearest sectioning content or sectioning root element.
- `<main>`: Represents the dominant content of the `<body>`.
- `<address>`: Provides contact information for a person or organization.

### Text Content
- `<p>`: Defines a paragraph.
- `<h1>` to `<h6>`: Define HTML headings.
- `<blockquote>`: Defines a section that is quoted from another source.
- `<ol>`: Defines an ordered list.
- `<ul>`: Defines an unordered list.
- `<li>`: Defines a list item.
- `<dl>`: Defines a description list.
- `<dt>`: Defines a term in a description list.
- `<dd>`: Describes the term in a description list.
- `<figure>`: Specifies self-contained content, like illustrations, diagrams, photos, code listings, etc.
- `<figcaption>`: Defines a caption for a `<figure>` element.
- `<div>`: Defines a division or a section in an HTML document.

### Inline Text Semantics
- `<a>`: Defines a hyperlink.
- `<strong>`: Defines important text.
- `<em>`: Defines emphasized text.
- `<br>`: Inserts a single line break.
- `<span>`: Defines a section in a document.
- `<mark>`: Highlights text.
- `<small>`: Defines smaller text.
- `<del>`: Defines text that has been deleted from a document.
- `<ins>`: Defines text that has been inserted into a document.
- `<sub>`: Defines subscripted text.
- `<sup>`: Defines superscripted text.
- `<b>`: Defines bold text.
- `<i>`: Defines italic text.
- `<u>`: Defines underlined text.
- `<abbr>`: Defines an abbreviation.
- `<code>`: Defines a piece of computer code.
- `<pre>`: Defines preformatted text.
- `<cite>`: Defines the title of a work.